  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero"><h1>Butter vs Oil in Cooking</h1><p>Choosing the right fat for your dish.</p></div>

    <h2>When to Use Each</h2>
    <p>Butter offers unparalleled flavor and richness, making it ideal for baking, sauces, and finishing dishes. Oils, particularly refined ones, are better for high-heat cooking like searing and frying because they lack the milk solids that burn easily in butter.</p>
    <h2>The Magic of Brown Butter</h2>
    <p>Cooking butter until its milk solids toast creates brown butter (beurre noisette), adding a deep, nutty complexity to both savory and sweet dishes.</p>
    <h2>Clarified Butter and Ghee</h2>
    <p>By removing the water and milk solids from butter, you get clarified butter or ghee. This process raises the smoke point significantly, combining the flavor of butter with the high-heat capabilities of a refined oil.</p>
